The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Loose Change
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           LOOSE CHANGE
                              
	 The State Bank of India (SBI) will launch mobile banking services within a month. The bank has prepared the technology platform to roll out the service. The SBI will initially offer basic banking services such as money transfer, account status enquiry and cheque book order through mobile banking. Other services such as bill payment and buying movie and travel tickets will be introduced later. The SBI has nearly one crore customers in the country. At present, Standard Chartered Bank, Barclays, the Union Bank of India and Yes Bank provide this service.                             
	 The Corporation Bank has launched a reverse mortgage loan scheme, Corp Shelter, for people aged 60 years and above. The borrower should be the owner of a residential property with a clear title and free from encumbrances. The house should be insured against fire and natural calamity at the borrowers cost. The maximum loan amount for the scheme is Rs 50 lakh at a 10 per cent interest rate.                            
	 HDFC Mutual Fund has fixed April 21 as the date for dividend under its two fixed maturity plans  HDFC FMP 17M November 2006 (Retail amp; Wholesale Plans) and HDFC FMP 16M December 2006 Retail Plan. These plans are under HDFC FMP-Series II.                                                                                                                              
